# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: compound-steam-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:compound-steam-engine/adiabatic-process] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:compound-steam-engine/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In October 1825 the Preußisch-Rheinische Dampfschiffahrts-Gesellschaft (PRDG) ordered two steamboats at the Nederlandsche Stoomboot Maatschappij (Dutch Steamboat Comp.) A later overview suggests that *Agrippina* was part of this initial order by the PRDG.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] It also showed that she was comparatively large for a steamboat.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Already in 1828, PRDG's plan was to use *Agrippina* as the third boat between Cologne and Mainz.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] This would allow the company to make 240 trips a year instead of only 160.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The engines for *Agrippina* were ordered at Taylor & Martineau in London.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] These were to be more powerful than those of her predecessors, so *Agrippina* would more easily get upstream.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] This would be achieved by using high steam pressure, which renders much more effective horse-power than the low pressure steam engines of the ships that PRDG already had.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Taylor & Martineau was known for high pressure steam engines, as well as for horizontal steam engines.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The innovative engines of *Agrippina* proved much heavier than expected, and so her draft increased from 2.5 feet to 3.5 feet.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] After loading coal her draft was even 4'2".
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Meanwhile, the partnership Taylor & Martineau was dissolved in 1827.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In late May 1828, *Agrippina* first arrived in Cologne.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The PRDG was quick to point out defects, and so *Agrippina* returned to Rotterdam in order to be made more suitable for the Rhine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On 27 June 1828, *Agrippina* arrived in Mainz, where she was tested again.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] When PRDG observed that *Agrippina* had more draft than expected, the company refused to accept her, and a commission of experts was formed to investigate.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In late August, she was still in the harbor, because PRDG did not dare to use her in the service between Cologne and Mainz after a second test had led to negative results.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] As built, *Agrippina* showed more problems than only high draft.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The machinery took up so much place, that the boat could not carry carriages.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] It also used an extraordinary amount of coal, about 300 hundredweight a day.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Furthermore, *Agrippina* was 13 hours slower than *Concordia* on the stretch from Cologne to Mainz.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] It would mean that on the two steaming days of this stretch, *Agrippina* would have to leave six hours earlier on each day.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The problem for PRDG was that the contract had been made without proper technical specifications.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In the end a deal was made whereby PRDG would trade in *Agrippina* for NSM's *De Rijn* and pay the high price of 165,000 guilders.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] By 31 October, *Agrippina* had been accepted back by the NSM, and had left Cologne for Rotterdam.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The details of the deal, including the delivery of her replacement on 1 April, were published on 21 February 1829.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] After being returned to NSM, *Agrippina* was used to tow barges between Rotterdam and Wesel or Ruhrort.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Her very heavy engines did not function well under average pressure.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The boat was very slow, and she consumed an extraordinary amount of coal.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] NSM then decided to radically change *Agrippina*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The failure of *Agrippina* financially affected NSM.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In the deal with PRDG it had lost a steamboat.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] NSM then discovered that she had no commercially viable use for *Agrippina*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Meanwhile, Roentgen undoubtedly knew of the ban on the use of high-pressure steam engines on passenger ships, which the Dutch government would issue in 1829.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] By late 1828 NSM was in financial trouble, even defaulting on loan repayments.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The idea of lending even more money, so *Agrippina* could get a new low-pressure engine was probably not realistic.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] What could be done was to use the high-pressure engines of *Agrippina* in a tugboat.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] NSM had a big tugboat lying around somewhere, the unfinished *Hercules*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In January 1829, or even earlier, Roentgen got the idea to place the high-pressure cylinders of *Agrippina* in *Hercules*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The idea was that Hercules would then tow *Agrippina*, which had good passenger accommodation.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] This way, NSM could make money without big new investments.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The re-use of *Agrippina'*s high-pressure cylinders in combination with a low-pressure cylinder led to the first effective compound steam engine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] When *Hercules* was first put into service, she could only use her high pressure cylinders.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On 17 August 1829 *Hercules* left Rotterdam for Düsseldorf towing *Agrippina*, which had been turned into a dumb barge with luxury passenger accommodation.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On 20 August the combination reached Düsseldorf where grand duchess Helen of Russia disembarked.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The service of *Hercules* and *Agrippina* was regularly scheduled for September 1829.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] However, the size of both vessels made the combination troublesome.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] *Hercules* was then changed for a different mode of transport, and *Agrippina* had failed again.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] After failing as a dumb barge, *Agrippina* probably spent most of her time laying around at Fijenoord shipyard.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In 1832, there was a plan to borrow 40,000 guilders to create new engines for her, but the loan failed.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In June 1833, a new plan to borrow for new engines succeeded.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] From this information, we have to assume that the new *Agrippina* which appeared later on, was a rebuild of the old one.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] This is not certain but is supported by the lifespan of the ship.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The new engines of *Agrippina* were later reported to have been of the compound type.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The high-pressure cylinder was new, and the low-pressure cylinder was taken from *Atlas*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The original plan for new engines somehow seems to have got a much wider scope.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In the second half of 1834, somebody visited Fijenoord.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] He dated a report of his visit to 28 October 1834.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] During his visit he observed the 190 feet long steam*ship* Pylades in the harbor, and on a parallel slipway, a 220 feet long steam*boat*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The latter was about to be launched the next day, and to enter service in the early spring of 1835.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On a later visit in 1835 our visitor noted that the steamboat had indeed been commissioned, and that he had made a trip with her in summer.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] He also noted that *De Nederlander* had been lengthened by 15 meters, and that another boat would be lengthened by 18 meters.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] NSM was obviously into lengthening her steamboats.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Longer vessels were made possible by the use of iron elements and probably helped to diminish the draft of the boats.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In July 1835 *Agrippina* was in service between Rotterdam and Cologne.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] She was described as a colossal, but elegant boat of '200 feet' length, with three masts and 50 beds.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The length of 200 feet seems to contradict her identification as the steamboat observed at Fijenoord in 1834.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Here, the problem is in the use of different feet.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The Fijenoord shipyard used English measurements for machines and boilers, but Amsterdam feet of 0.2831 m for shipbuilding.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] If the observers in Cologne used the common Rheinfuß of 0.314 m, the identification of the 220 feet long boat observed in 1834 with our *Agrippina* is even more solid.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The difference between 220 Amsterdam feet and 200 Rheinfuß is less than 50 cm.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On 27 August 1836 *Agrippina*, commanded by Captain Cranenbroek left Düsseldorf with the third Garde Landwehr battalion on board.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Menckhoff, and was about to join in large scale maneuvers near Koblenz.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] For the occasion *Agrippina* had been decorated with the arms of Prussia.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The use of *Agrippina* was of great use to the men of the battalion.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On 28 August the about 600 men of the battalion arrived in Koblenz.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In July 1837 *Agrippina* transported the King of Württemberg and the princesses Maria and Sophia, as well as a large escort from Cologne to The Hague.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The company travelled by the names of Count and Countesses of Teck, so it did not turn into a state visit.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On 6 July the company arrived in Nijmegen, where it spent the night in the Logement de Plaats Roijaal.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On the morrow it continued towards The Hague on board *Agrippina*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In 1837 Friedrich Karl von Strombeck made a trip on board *Agrippina*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] At the NSM office on the Boompjes, he bought a ticket for a trip to Mainz.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] It cost 26 Prussian Thaler and 5 groschen for a place in the great cabin.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] From Cologne, a ship of the PRDG would bring him to Mainz.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On 13 July at 8 AM *Agrippina* left Rotterdam.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Von Strombeck was impressed by the steamer with its 120 horse power.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The company on deck reminded him of the arcades of a busy Spa town.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] There were many, mostly Dutch ladies, young and old in elegant dresses.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Some young men wore Italian boater hats.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Many older man wore travel hats, while some even wore spurs and a horse whip.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Von Strombeck found the great cabin very elegant.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] It had large mirrors, polished mahogany, and brass ornaments.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On the tables were newspapers in three or four languages.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] It even had a small library, and when a young lady asked Von Strombeck what he did, he 'could satisfy his author's vanity' by showing her his entry in the Brockhaus Enzyklopädie.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Near Dordrecht the rudder hit something, and the cogwheel that connected to the rudder broke in three pieces.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] A temporary fix was made with ropes and pulleys and six sailors pulling to move the rudder.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] After many stops, *Agrippina* reached Nijmegen in the evening, where Von Strombeck slept in the Hotel des Pays Bas.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] At 7am, *Agrippina* continued to Cologne.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] At many stations, she laid still for some time, and lowered her stairs.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Small boats with red flags then quickly transferred passengers.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] At Emmerich am Rhein a stop was made for customs, which checked part of the luggage.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] At dusk the steamer was near Duisburg, Von Strombeck went to bed in a small room in front of the machinery, with 8 or 10 small beds.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] There was an argand lamp and a facility to wash.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Somewhere in the night, the makeshift fix for the rudder broke, and *Agrippina* hit something, causing the lamp to be extinguished.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Von Strombeck did not get much sleep, especially because of the noise that the transfer of cargo in Düsseldorf made.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In the morning he saw the 'smarter' passengers which had spent the night on the couches of the great cabin.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] *Agrippina* then reached Cologne before noon.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Here Von Strombeck spent the night at the Hotel de Belle Vue in Deutz.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] From 13 to 16 August 1837 the city of Mainz organized a huge celebration to commemorate the invention of the printing press by Johannes Gutenberg.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On 15 August there was a maritime spectacle on the Rhine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Nearly 300 vessels formed an immense rectangle within which the games took place.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] There were about 50,000 spectators, many on board the vessels.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Near the quay was a new steamboat with princes and princesses, invitees, and local authorities.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] This boat was the podium for the awards, and would of course be christened *Gutenberg*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Across from the *Gutenberg* lay 'the beautiful Dutch three-master' *Agrippina*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On board she had a numerous military band, the direction of the games, and a number of guns operated by the Austrian artillery.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The opening event consisted of 12 boats rowing the competitors, who stood at the sterns, dressed as Neapolitan fisherman.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The first game consisted of recovering two flags and seizing a large eel.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The first flag was to be gained by climbing a rope dangling from the yard of the main mast of *Agrippina*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The other flag was at the end of a 40 feet bowsprit.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The eel dangled from a rope spanned high over the games area, and had to be grabbed by quickly rowing a boat under it, and then jumping to grab it.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The main game was about the competitors using their lance to push their adversary into the water.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In September 1838, the Dutch church minister (*predikant*) H.F.T.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Fockens made a trip along the Rhine together with his brother, who was an officer in the Dutch navy.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Fockens published about this trip in a literary magazine in 1839.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] After travelling to Cologne by stagecoach, the brothers took *Agrippina* from Cologne upstream.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The brothers paid 15 Thaler or 27 guilders for a place in the first cabin.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Some English passengers had hired the best place, the pavilion, and parked their three coaches on the front deck.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In Bonn, the brothers stayed at the Hotel de Trêves on the Great Market.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Fockens main interest was to visit the University of Bonn, and to meet the staff of the faculty of Theology.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Apart from that, they also visited the regular tourist attractions like Rolandseck and climbed the Drachenfels.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] At 9 in the evening, the brothers again boarded a steamboat in Königswinter and spent the night on board.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In the early morning of 14 September, they arrived in Koblenz, where they spent the night in Hotel Bellevue.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] At 6:30 AM on 15 September, the brothers embarked on a steamboat from Koblenz to Biebrich.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On board was the usual very international company of tourists.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Between Sankt Goar and Kaub the boat's staff often played a trumpet and fired cannon to hear the echo of the mountains.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] From the wall cannon were fired in salute at the steamboat, which had first come into service, and was called *Agrippina*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] After disembarking at Biebrich, the brothers continued to Frankfurt by coach.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Here, they again boarded *Agrippina* downstream on 17 September.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] After 10.5 hours they were back in Cologne.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Here they boarded a steamboat of the Dampfschiffahrts-Gesellschaft für den Nieder- und Mittelrhein to Arnhem.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In 1841, the steamboat season began early, when NSM's *Agrippina* and *Ludwig* arrived in Nijmegen on 27 January.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] At about 3pm on 25 September 1841, two steamboats were seen approaching the town of Rees in Germany.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The heavy exhaust plumes announced that both were making a lot of steam, even while they were going downstream.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] It were *Drusus* of the IJssel Stoomboot Maatschappij, and NSM's *Agrippina*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Very near to Rees, *Agrippina* succeeded in passing Drusus to get to the pier.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Because of her speed, *Agrippina* then turned too quickly and too short, making the pavilion, which was on the stern, hit the pier.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The damage was reportedly heavy to both ship and pier.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On 2 October, the NSM reacted to the report by stating that *Agrippina* arrived on schedule on the 26th, and left again according to schedule on the 27th.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] According to NSM, there was only some damage to the artistic carvings on the stern, and to the rear fence, and lifeboat.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] It was also noted that *Agrippina* was much faster than *Drusus*, and often overtook her on the Rhine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Furthermore, Rees was not a regular stop for *Drusus*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Whatever the truth of the accident, after some more trips, *Agrippina* left Rotterdam under Captain de Ruyter on 19 October.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] She then suddenly became very leaky on her port side while she was near Tiel.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Within in a few moments, there were several feet of water in the cabins.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The captain then saw no other option but to beach *Agrippina* near Wamel.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Attempts were made to safe the 120 tons of cargo, by bringing it on deck and transloading it on barges, but most of it was ruined.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The later explanation for the accident was that the boat had hit a submerged beam, which had bent inwards an iron part of the machine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The movement of the paddle wheel would then have caused this part to create a leak.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Some newspapers had details about there being 4 feet of water in the hold before *Agrippina* was beached, and that the cargo consisted mainly of highly perishable sugar and saltpeter.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The shift from wooden barges to iron barges was a development that would allow cargo transport on the Rhine to withstand the competition of the railways and road transport.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The NSM had tried establish a tug service on the Rhine since 1825, but this was not commercially viable without government subsidies.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] NSM then became the first company to use its own iron barges instead of towing wooden barges owned by others.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The idea was that these iron barges could be made much bigger than wooden barges, and could so economize on staff.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] They would also be used year-round, instead of only when the wind was unfavorable.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Because the hull weight was less, they would not have as much draft as wooden boats.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Later experiments showed that with the same speed and expense of coal, iron barges could transport 50% more cargo.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] All combined, the iron barge would make towing cargo upstream profitable.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In 1841, NSM launched the iron barge *Rijn I*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] She measured 180 by 24 feet, and had a depth of hold of 11 English feet.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In 1841 *Rijn I* made a trip up the Rhine towed by horses.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On 24 December 1841, she started a trip up the Rhine towed by *Agrippina*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] On 26 May both arrived in Cologne, *Agrippina* towing *Rijn I* of captain J.J.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] *Rijn I* was loaded with 4,849 cwt, giving her a draft of 3.75 feet.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The trip had been accomplished in the short time of 38 hours of steaming.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] It was the first trip of a towed iron barge on the Rhine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In 1842 *Agrippina* also towed iron barges.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In the early morning of 21 October 1843, a coal barge that descended the Rhine hit *Agrippina*, which was lying before the NSM office at De Boompjes.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The barge sunk immediately, and had to be raised.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] *Agrippina* probably suffered little, because on 16 November she arrived in Mannheim towing the iron *Rhein II*.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] The NSM had a close relation with the Mannheim entrepreneur Mathias Stinnes.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] Stinnes owned mines and was the largest barge owner on the Rhine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] When NSM was in financial trouble and diminished shipping activities, it rented out *Agrippina* and *Concordia* to Stinnes in 1844.
[src:compound-steam-engine/agrippina-1827] In 1850 or 1851 a new steamboat named *Agrippina* was laid down at Fijenoord.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] Alexander Carnegie Kirk was the eldest son of Rev.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] John Kirk (died 1858) and Christian Guthrie, née Carnegie, (died 1865).
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] The naturalist John Kirk was his younger brother.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] Kirk married Ada Waller at Croydon in 1869 and they had six children.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] In 1850, Kirk began a five-year apprenticeship with Robert Napier and Sons.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] In 1861, he became chief draughtsman at Maudslay, Sons and Field in London but this seems to have lasted less than a year.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] Later in 1861 he became an engineering manager in the shale-oil industry, working for James Young.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] During this employment he developed an oil shale retort and a refrigeration technology, involving the delivery of ether.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] The latter was to address production problems stemming from summer heat.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] In 1865 he joined the management of James Aitken and Company, an engine works in Glasgow.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] In 1870 he was appointed manager of the John C.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] After returning to the Napier firm as a senior partner in 1877, his work was thereafter focused on marine engineering.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] His triple-expansion engines as designed for the steamship *Propontis* were unsuccessful, but his subsequent versions of the engine design, particularly those designed for the steamship *Aberdeen*, are credited as technological breakthroughs.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] He served as the President of The Institution of Engineers and Shipbuilders in Scotland from 1887 to 1889.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alexander-carnegie-kirk] In 2020 he was inducted into the Scottish Engineering Hall of Fame.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-george-de-glehn] He invented the Glehn system of compounding, and De Glehn types were built in large numbers in France, and were also built in smaller numbers in Belgium, Germany, New Zealand, and Russia, see Compound locomotive.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-george-de-glehn] Compounding lost favour from the 1900s, being replaced by superheating.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-george-de-glehn] However André Chapelon rebuilt many of the French De Glehn compounds from 1929 onwards.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-george-de-glehn] Alfred De Glehn was one of the twelve children of Robert von Glehn, a Prussian nobleman originally from the Baltic provinces, whose family had estates near Tallinn in Estonia, who had settled in England and married a Scotswoman.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-george-de-glehn] Their house in Sydenham, London, was a meeting place of artistic, literary and musical people, including George Grove, Arthur Sullivan, Jenny Lind, and J.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-george-de-glehn] Louise Creighton, an author and activist, was one of De Glehn's sisters.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-george-de-glehn] One of his brothers, Alexander von Glehn, was a coffee-merchant and built narrow-gauge railways in France.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-george-de-glehn] Alexander was the treasurer of the Protestant Evangelical Society of Relief in Paris which provided help to victims of the Franco-Prussian War, and Alexander’s son Wilfrid de Glehn was a British painter.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-george-de-glehn] Alfred De Glehn changed the nobiliary particle in his name from "von" to "de" when he settled in France.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-george-de-glehn] Other members of the family remaining in England followed his example about 1917, during the First World War, when Britain was at war with Germany.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-george-de-glehn] De Glehn died at his home at Mulhouse in Alsace at the age of 88.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-george-de-glehn] His house had been commandeered as the German district headquarters during the war.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] Alfred Holt was one of six brothers, born to George Holt and his wife, Emma.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] In 1866, he and his brother, Philip Holt founded the Alfred Holt and Company and the Ocean Steam Ship Company, which owned and operated the majority of the company's vessels.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] Alfred Holt & Co later became Blue Funnel Line.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] One of his other brothers, George Holt, was also a noted Liverpool merchant and ship owner.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] His youngest brother, Robert Durning Holt, was Mayor of Liverpool.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] Holt served an apprenticeship under the chief engineer of the Liverpool & Manchester Railway, learning the basics of both mechanical and civil engineering.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] On finishing his apprenticeship, he established himself as an engineering consultant, and soon became involved in ship management.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] The efficiencies of compound steam engines, which were widely used in railway locomotives, were not available to steamships as the Board of trade limited the steam pressures of marine boilers to about 20 psi (140 kPa).
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] Not only did Holt understand the well-known benefits of higher steam pressures running compound engines, but he also had the negotiating skills to gain the approval of the Board of Trade to put this into effect.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] The result was *Cleator*, the testbed for these ideas, running at 60 psi (410 kPa).
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] Holt then set about designing a steamship for the China trade.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] This was a route worked almost entirely by sail.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] The Peninsular and Oriental Steam Navigation Company had a steamship route to China from Britain that went along the Mediterranean, with an overland section to the north end of the Red Sea and then to China by sea.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] A few auxiliary steamships sailed to China round the Cape of Good Hope, using their steam engines in light winds.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] The more prominent cargo vessels on this route were the clippers engaged in the tea trade, but many ordinary merchant sailing vessels also sailed to China.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] The passage from London to China is about 14,000 nautical miles.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] The problem for a steamer was to have space for enough coal for this distance, but still carry a commercial amount of cargo.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] Holt achieved a big increase in efficiency that made this possible.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] He married his first wife, Catherine Long in 1865.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] They had a daughter, Jane (1867–1922), who married the marine biologist William Abbott Herdman; a son, George, who became one of the managers of the Blue Funnel Line; and another son, who died in his teens.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] After Catherine's death in 1869, Alfred Holt married her cousin, Frances Long (in 1871), with whom he had two more sons.
[src:compound-steam-engine/alfred-holt] The youngest son, also named Alfred (1877–1931), became a Reader in Chemistry at the University of Liverpool.
[src:compound-steam-engine/anatole-mallet] In 1876 he introduced a series of small two-cylinder compound 0-4-2T tank locomotives for the Bayonne-Anglet-Biarritz Railway in France.
[src:compound-steam-engine/anatole-mallet] He subsequently designed an articulated compound system with a rigid chassis at the rear carrying two high-pressure cylinders, and two low-pressure ones mounted on a swivelling front truck.
[src:compound-steam-engine/anatole-mallet] This was patented in 1884 with full rights granted in 1885.
[src:compound-steam-engine/anatole-mallet] This was first used for a series of 600 mm (1 ft 11+5⁄8 in) narrow gauge locomotives specially built by the Decauville Company in 1888 for the Paris Exposition of 1889.
[src:compound-steam-engine/anatole-mallet] This arrangement became known as the Mallet locomotive.
[src:compound-steam-engine/anatole-mallet] The final developments of these in the USA were some of the largest steam locomotives ever built.
[src:compound-steam-engine/anatole-mallet] A third compound locomotive, less well-known, was a tandem compound developed in 1890 for SACM as a collaboration with Alfred de Glehn and the Russian A.
[src:compound-steam-engine/anatole-mallet] The high and low pressure cylinders were mounted on a common axis, with the high pressure ahead.
[src:compound-steam-engine/anatole-mallet] Unlike the US tandem compounds, the high and low pressure cylinders were cross-connected between sides, which also required them to be receiver compounds with an intermediate reservoir as a pair of curved pipes passing through the smokebox.
[src:compound-steam-engine/anatole-mallet] Large numbers of these, mostly a 2-8-0 derivative, were built for Russian and Hungarian railways making them the most-produced type of tandem compound locomotive.
[src:compound-steam-engine/anatole-mallet] Kordina's design for Hungarian State Railways was a similar 4-4-0, although outside-framed and with the low-pressure cylinders ahead of the high pressure.
[src:compound-steam-engine/anatole-mallet] He was awarded the Elliott Cresson Medal of The Franklin Institute in 1908, and he was elected an honorary member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in 1912.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] A **compound steam engine** unit is a type of steam engine where steam is expanded in two or more stages.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] A typical arrangement for a compound engine is that the steam is first expanded in a high-pressure (HP) cylinder, then having given up heat and losing pressure, it exhausts directly into one or more larger-volume low-pressure (LP) cylinders.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Multiple-expansion engines employ additional cylinders, of progressively lower pressure, to extract further energy from the steam.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Invented in 1781, this technique was first employed on a Cornish beam engine in 1804.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Around 1850, compound engines were introduced into Lancashire textile mills.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] In a single-expansion (or 'simple') steam engine, the high-pressure steam enters the cylinder at boiler pressure through an inlet valve.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The steam pressure forces the piston down the cylinder, until the valve shuts (e.g. after 25% of the piston's stroke).
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] After the steam supply is cut off the trapped steam continues to expand, pushing the piston to the end of its stroke, where the exhaust valve opens and expels the partially depleted steam to the atmosphere, or to a condenser.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] This "cut-off" allows much more work to be extracted, since the expansion of the steam is doing additional work beyond that done by the steam at boiler pressure.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] An earlier cut-off increases the expansion ratio, which in principle allows more energy to be extracted and increases efficiency.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Ideally, the steam would expand adiabatically, and the temperature would drop corresponding to the volume increase.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] However, in practice the material of the surrounding cylinder acts as a heat reservoir, cooling the steam in the earlier part of the expansion and heating it in the later part.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] These irreversible heat flows decrease the efficiency of the process, so that, beyond a certain point, further increasing the expansion ratio would actually decrease efficiency, in addition to decreasing the mean effective pressure and thus the power of the engine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] A solution to the dilemma was invented in 1804 by British engineer Arthur Woolf, who patented his *Woolf high pressure compound engine* in 1805.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] In the compound engine, high-pressure steam from the boiler first expands in a high-pressure (HP) cylinder and then enters one or more subsequent lower pressure (LP) cylinders.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The complete expansion of the steam occurs across multiple cylinders and, as there is less expansion in each cylinder, the steam cools less in each cylinder, making higher expansion ratios practical and increasing the efficiency of the engine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] There are other advantages: as the temperature range is smaller, cylinder condensation is reduced.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Loss due to condensation is restricted to the LP cylinder.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Pressure difference is less in each cylinder so there is less steam leakage at the piston and valves.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The turning moment is more uniform, so balancing is easier and a smaller flywheel may be used.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Only the smaller HP cylinder needs to be built to withstand the highest pressure, which reduces the overall weight.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Similarly, components are subject to less strain, so they can be lighter.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The reciprocating parts of the engine are lighter, reducing the engine vibrations.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The compound could be started at any point in the cycle, and in the event of mechanical failure the compound could be reset to act as a simple, and thus keep running.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] To derive equal work from lower-pressure steam requires a larger cylinder volume as this steam occupies a greater volume.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Therefore, the bore, and in rare cases the stroke as well, are increased in low-pressure cylinders, resulting in larger cylinders.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Double-expansion (usually just known as 'compound') engines expand the steam in two stages, but this does not imply that all such engines have two cylinders.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The adoption of compounding was widespread for stationary industrial units where the need was for increased power at decreasing cost, and almost universal for marine engines after 1880.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] It was not widely used in railway locomotives where it was often perceived as complicated and unsuitable for the harsh railway operating environment and limited space afforded by the loading gauge (particularly in Britain).
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Compounding was never common on British railways and not employed at all after 1930, but was used in a limited way in many other countries.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] It is a logical extension of the compound engine (described above) to split the expansion into yet more stages to increase efficiency.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The result is the **multiple-expansion engine**.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Such engines use either three or four expansion stages and are known as *triple-* and *quadruple-expansion engines* respectively.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] These engines use a series of double-acting cylinders of progressively increasing diameter and/or stroke and hence volume.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] These cylinders are designed to divide the work into three or four equal portions, one for each expansion stage.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The adjacent image shows an animation of a triple-expansion engine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The steam travels through the engine from left to right.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The valve chest for each of the cylinders is to the left of the corresponding cylinder.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Though the first mills were driven by water power, once steam engines were adopted the manufacturer no longer needed to site the mills by running water.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Cotton spinning required ever larger mills to fulfil the demand, and this drove the owners to demand increasingly powerful engines.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] When boiler pressure had exceeded 60 psi, compound engines achieved a thermo-dynamic advantage, but it was the mechanical advantages of the smoother stroke that was the deciding factor in the adoption of compounds.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] In 1859, there was 75,886 ihp (indicated horsepower) of engines in mills in the Manchester area, of which 32,282 ihp was provided by compounds though only 41,189 ihp was generated from boilers operated at over 60psi.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] To generalise, between 1860 and 1926 all Lancashire mills were driven by compounds.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The last compound built was by Buckley and Taylor for Wye No.2 mill, Shaw.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] This engine was a cross-compound design to 2,500 ihp, driving a 24 ft, 90 ton flywheel, and operated until 1965.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] In the marine environment, the general requirement was for autonomy and increased operating range, as ships had to carry their coal supplies.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The old salt-water boiler was thus no longer adequate and had to be replaced by a closed fresh-water circuit with condenser.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The result from 1880 onwards was the **multiple-expansion engine** using three or four expansion stages (*triple-* and *quadruple-expansion engines*).
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] These engines used a series of double-acting cylinders of progressively increasing diameter and/or stroke (and hence volume) designed to divide the work into three or four, as appropriate, equal portions for each expansion stage.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Where space is at a premium, two smaller cylinders of a large sum volume might be used for the low-pressure stage.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Multiple-expansion engines typically had the cylinders arranged in-line, but various other formations were used.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] In the late 19th century, the Yarrow–Schlick–Tweedy balancing 'system' was used on some marine triple-expansion engines.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Y–S–T engines divided the low-pressure expansion stages between two cylinders, one at each end of the engine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] This allowed the crankshaft to be better balanced, resulting in a smoother, faster-responding engine which ran with less vibration.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] This made the 4-cylinder triple-expansion engine popular with large passenger liners (such as the *Olympic* class), but was ultimately replaced by the virtually vibration-free steam turbine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The development of this type of engine was important for its use in steamships as by exhausting to a condenser the water could be reclaimed to feed the boiler, which was unable to use seawater.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Land-based steam engines could simply exhaust much of their steam, as feed water was usually readily available.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Prior to and during World War II, the expansion engine dominated marine applications where high vessel speed was not essential.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] It was superseded by the steam turbine when speed was required, such as for warships and ocean liners.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] HMS *Dreadnought* of 1905 was the first major warship to replace the proven technology of the reciprocating engine with the then-novel steam turbine.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] While designs for compound locomotives may date as far back as James Samuel's 1856 patent for a "continuous expansion locomotive", the practical history of railway compounding begins with Anatole Mallet's designs in the 1870s.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Mallet locomotives were operated in the United States up to the end of mainline steam by the Norfolk and Western Railway.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The designs of Alfred George de Glehn in France also saw significant use, especially in the rebuilds of André Chapelon.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] A wide variety of compound designs were tried around 1900, but most were short-lived in popularity, due to their complexity and maintenance liability.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] In the 20th century the superheater was widely adopted, and the vast majority of steam locomotives were simple-expansion (with some compound locomotives converted to simple).
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] It was realised by engineers that locomotives at steady speed were worked most efficiently with a wide-open regulator and early cut-off, the latter being set via the reversing gear.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] A locomotive operating at very early cut-off of steam (e.g. at 15% of the piston stroke) allows maximum expansion of the steam, with less wasted energy at the end of the stroke.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Superheating eliminates the condensation and rapid loss of pressure that would otherwise occur with such expansion.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Large American locomotives used two cross-compound steam-driven air compressors, e.g. the Westinghouse 8 1/2" 150-D, for the train brakes.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The presentation follows Sommerfeld's textbook, which contains a diagram (Figure 17) that is not reproduced for copyright reasons.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Consider a four-cylinder engine on a ship.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Let *x* be the vertical direction, *z* be the fore–aft direction, and *y* be the port–starboard direction.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Let the four cylinders be mounted in a row along the *z* axis, so that their pistons are pointed downwards.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The pistons are connected to the same crankshaft via long vertical rods.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Now, as the engine operates, the vertical position of cylinder i is equal to $x_{i}$ .
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] As each cylinder moves up and down, it exerts a vertical force on its mounting frame equaling $M_{i}{\ddot {x}}_{i}$ .
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The YST system aims to make sure that the total of all four forces cancels out as exactly as possible.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] This gives us eight equations to solve, which is in general possible if there are at least eight variables of the system that we can vary.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Of the variables of the system, $M_{i},r_{i}$ are fixed by the design of the cylinders.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] Also, the absolute values of $a_{2},a_{3},a_{4}$ do not matter, only their ratios matter.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The YST system requires at least four cylinders.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] With three cylinders, the same derivation gives us only six variables to vary, which is insufficient to solve all eight equations.
[src:compound-steam-engine/compound-steam-engine] The YST system is used on ships such as the SS Kaiser Wilhelm der Grosse and SS Deutschland (1900).
